lines.value: there are currently three sources of moon rocks on earth 1 those collected by us apollo missions 2 samples returned by the soviet union luna missions and 3 rocks that were ejected naturally from the lunar surface by cratering events and subsequently fell to earth as lunar meteorites
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: during the six apollo surface excursions 2415 samples weighing 382 kg 842 lb were collected the majority by apollo 15 16 and 17
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the three luna spacecraft returned with an additional 326 g 0.66 lb of samples
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: over 90 lunar meteorites have been found on earth as of late 2006 comprising over 30 kg of material
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the apollo moon rocks were collected using a variety of tools including hammers rakes scoops tongs and core tubes
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: most were photographed prior to collection to record the condition in which they were found
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: they were placed inside sample bags and then a special environmental sample container for return to the earth to protect them from contamination
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: in general the rocks collected from the moon are extremely old compared to rocks found on earth as measured by radiometric dating techniques
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the youngest is older than the oldest rocks seen on earth
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: they range in age from 3.2 billion years from the basalt samples from the lunar mares up to 4.6 billion years in the highlands therefore representing samples from a very early period in the formation of the solar system
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the rocks possess characteristics very similar to rock on earth particularly in the amounts of oxygen isotopes
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: but rocks from the moon tend to be relatively low in iron and are depleted in volatile chemicals such as potassium or sodium and are completely lacking in water
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: among the new minerals found on the moon was armalcolite which is named for the three astronauts on the apollo 11 mission armstrong aldrin and collins
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the main repository for the apollo moon rocks is the lunar sample building at the lyndon b johnson space center in houston texas
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: for safe keeping there is also a smaller collection stored at brooks air force base at san antonio texas
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: most of the rocks are stored in nitrogen to keep them free of moisture
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: they are only handled indirectly using special tools
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: moon rocks collected during the course of lunar exploration are currently considered priceless
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: in 1993 three small fragments weighing 0.2 g from luna 16 were sold for us$442500
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: in 2002 a safe was stolen from the lunar sample building containing minute samples of lunar and martian material
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the samples were recovered and in 2003 nasa estimated the value of these samples for the court case at about $1 million for 285 g 10 oz of material
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: moon rocks in the form of lunar meteorites although expensive are widely sold and traded among private collectors
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: a couple of hundred small samples were mounted and presented to national governments and us governors
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: at least one of these was later stolen sold and recovered
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: other samples went to select museums including the national air and space museum the kansas cosmosphere and space center and to the visitor center at kennedy space center where it is possible to touch a piece of the moon which is in fact a small moon rock concreted into a pillar in the center of a bank vault that visitors tour
lines.name: Latin
